ned to detailed criticism as major theoretical movements emerged in the 1970s. In doing so, it provides a vital context for the contemporary practice of style-based criticism and challenges received notions of critical history, developing our understanding of a range of other key debates and concerns in the study of film.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFilm criticismzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aBritish culture.  aBritish journals.  aElsaesser.  aMovie.  aTales of Sound and Fury.  acultural shifts.  afilm criticism.  afilm style.  afilm viewing.  aliterary criticism.  amelodrama.  amise-en-scene.  apolitical shifts.  apostwar period.  avisual style.1 aGibbs, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610313040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526103130423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526103130/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles